fields.descriptive_line: Burne-Jones, E.C. Sketchbook containing studies for Paintings, stained glass, tapestry, mural decoration etc.
fields.physical_description: Sketchbook containing studies for Paintings, stained glass, tapestry, mural decoration etc.; sketches for a beaten silver plaque intended as a gift to Octavia Laura Mary Tennant on her marriage to the Rt. Hon. Alfred Lyttleton, P.C., K.C., M.P., together with detailed studies (some in colour) of a peacock, used in the design for her memorial tablet in the church of St. Andrew, Mells, Somerset. 146 pages of metallic surfaced paper, full-bound in black leather, blind tooled, with metal clasp, a pencil holder and pocket inside the front cover.
fields.dimensions: Height: 102 mm closed sketchbookbook, Width: 172 mm closed sketchbook, Depth: 12 mm closed sketchbook

fields.bibliography: Christofer Conrad and Hatje Cantz, Edward Burne-Jones. Das Irdische Paradies Stuttgart: Staatsgalerie Stuttgart, 2009. ISBN: 978-3-7757-2516-3 (Deutsch), 978-3-7757-2517-0 (English). Exhibition catalogue Lambert, Susan. Drawing: Technique & Purpose. London: Victoria & Albert Museum, 1981. p.46. The full text of the entry is as follows: ‘THINKING ON PAPER […] 131. Sir Edward Coley Burne-Jones (1833-1898); British Sketch-book. Open at four compositional sketches for the painting the ‘Baleful Head’ from the Perseus series Prepared pencil on prepared paper. Size of volume 10.2 x 17.2 cm VAM E.9-1955 (Given by Dr W. L. Hildburgh) The series of paintings illustrating the Legend of Perseus was commissioned in 1875 and the final version of the ‘Baleful Head’ was painted in 1886-7. A label inside the cover reads ‘Henry Penny’s improved metallic books. Best prepared paper warranted if written on with his prepared pencils to be as plain and as durable as ink. They will be found of great advantage to travellers and all persons who wish to preserve their writing’. The pencil is missing from its sleeve in the cover, but judging from the drawings it appears to have been a type of metal-point.’
fields.history_note: The original design for 'The Star of Bethlehem' tapestry and photographic enlargements used as cartoons for the stained glass panels in Birmingham Cathedral, 'The Nativity' and 'The Crucifixion' are E.5012-1919 and E.224 and 224-1911. A coloured replica of the uncoloured memorial tablet, in painted plaster on wood is P.85-1938.
